<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-01-09T16:56:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-01-09T16:56:00-05:00" n="148" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d148">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 711.21/220.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">Chargé <persName type="from">Harrison</persName> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Extract.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Bogota</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-01-09T17:00:00-04:56">
                                    <hi rend="italic">January 9, 1914, 5 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>I have seen the Minister for Foreign Affairs by appointment to receive
                            Colombia’s reply to the proposition of your December 19, 6 p.m.<note n="11" xml:id="d148fn11">
                                <ref target="frus1913#pg_328">Id. 328</ref>.</note> The Minister
                            apologized for the delay in answering, due to unavoidable absence of one
                            of the members of the Consultatory Commission of the Foreign Office. He
                            hopes to have a reply for me by the 13th instant.* * * Our negotiations
                            are, in fact, not with the Government but with the Commissioners,
                            representing all political parties, with whom the Government has but
                            little influence.* * *</p>
                        <p>Any concession the Department may be able to grant would go far toward a
                            settlement. If, however, the Department cannot accept their draft,<note n="12" xml:id="d148fn12">
                                <ref target="frus1913#pg_324">Id. 324</ref>.</note> a full frank
                            explanation of the reasons therefor would undoubtedly have a beneficial
                            effect.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Harrison</hi></signed>.</closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>